ce:section.ce:para:
The quantum yield (QY) of CDs has been reported to be sensitive to the preparation method and the surface chemistry involved. Many articles reported CDs with extremely high QY were obtained directly by heat treatment without any post-treatment processes [41,42]. However, our findings indicate that the QY of the liquid retained in the dialysis bag after dialysis was significantly lower than that of the three filtrates, which exhibited much higher QY values compared to the CDs (Table 6
                           ). In detail, the QY of F1 and F2 closely matched that of citric acid, with excitation and emission wavelengths consistent with the spectral characteristics of citric acid. HRMS analysis further confirmed the presence of citric acid (m/z = 154) in F1 and F2 (Fig. 9
                           ). For F3, while the optimal excitation wavelength was found to be similar to that of both CDs and N-GQDs, the optimal emission wavelength differed. Mass spectrometric analysis identified larger molecular weight species retained in the dialysis bag, suggesting the formation of high-molecular-weight aggregates, consistent with the characteristics of N-GQDs (Fig. 10
                           ). Interestingly, citrazinic acid was not detected either within or outside the dialysis bag, suggesting a transformation process under harsher hydrothermal conditions that likely removes low-molecular-weight compounds. Hence, these findings further highlight the critical role of dialysis in influencing the photophysical properties and quantum yield (QY) of CDs.
